WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standard reference for HDR Vivid, the HDR format developed
by the UHD World Association (UWA) of China and adopted by DVB. It defines
the dynamic metadata pipeline, the tone mapping algorithm, and the
colourimetry based on BT.2020 and ST.2084 PQ. HDR Vivid is poised to become
an ETSI global standard in 2026.

WHY IT EXISTS
HDR Vivid provides an open, royalty-free alternative to Dolby Vision and
HDR10+ for broadcast and OTT. With DVB publishing updated BlueBooks in
March 2026 incorporating T/UWA 005, HDR Vivid is now part of the global
broadcast infrastructure. GIOP includes it to ensure compatibility with
Chinese and DVB-compliant HDR content.

HOW IT WORKS
1. Dynamic Metadata:
   HDR Vivid uses display adaptation metadata similar to Dolby Vision
   Level 2/3 trims. Metadata includes:
     - Mastering display peak luminance
     - MaxCLL, MaxFALL per scene
     - Tone mapping curve parameters (lift, gamma, gain)
   The metadata format is defined in T/UWA 005 and is embedded as SEI
   messages in HEVC/VVC bitstreams or as JSON sidecar.

2. Tone Mapping Model:
   V_out = f(V_in, mastering_display_max, target_display_max, trim_params)
   The function f is a piecewise-Bezier curve parameterised by the trim
   metadata, ensuring smooth highlight roll-off and shadow preservation.

3. Colour Space:
   Primaries: BT.2020 (Rec.2020)
   Transfer function: ST.2084 PQ (or HLG for broadcast compatibility)
   White point: D65

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- DVB broadcast and OTT services
- Chinese UHD television and streaming (CCTV, iQiyi, Tencent Video)
- GIOP HDR delivery pipelines.

WHO USES IT
Broadcast engineers; streaming service architects; L2 Engineers
implementing HDR ODTs; L3 Colorists mastering for HDR Vivid delivery.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Provides an open HDR metadata standard now adopted by DVB, enabling
GIOP to deliver HDR content to the Chinese and global broadcast markets
without proprietary license fees.

